struct lfs_mdir_t (fields: pair, rev, tail, split, count, off, etag)
struct lfs_commit (fields used: block, off, ptag, crc, begin, end)
explanation:
To determine whether any statements in lfs_dir_compact are dead (i.e. can be removed without affecting observable behaviour) you must know the semantics and side-effects of all operations, the storage and in-memory state modified, and the relevant constants/macros that change control flow. For each listed symbol: 

- lfs_dir_needsrelocation: determines initial 'tired' flag; if it is always false/true then relocation code paths may be dead.
- lfs_pair_cmp: used to compare dir->pair against the superblock pair and to gate relocation; its exact comparison semantics decide whether branches are reachable/necessary.
- lfs_bd_erase: erases a block on the block device — a visible side-effect; needed to judge whether its call is removable.
- lfs_dir_commitprog: writes the directory header to the commit; has device-side effects and interacts with commit state.
- lfs_dir_traverse: drives writing of directory entries via callbacks; major side-effecting operation whose removal would change filesystem state.
- lfs_dir_commit_commit: the callback passed to lfs_dir_traverse; needed to know what traverse actually writes (side-effects) and whether the callback is essential.
- lfs_dir_commitattr: writes attribute records to the commit; has observable side-effects on storage.
- lfs_pair_isnull / lfs_pair_tole32 / lfs_pair_fromle32 / lfs_pair_swap: pair manipulations (checking, byte-ordering, swapping) change on-disk pointers and in-memory pair — needed to determine whether corresponding assignments are meaningful.
- lfs_gstate_xor / lfs_dir_getgstate / lfs_gstate_iszero / lfs_gstate_tole32: compute and test global state delta and serialize it; these affect stored global state and decide whether movestate tags are written.
- lfs_dir_commitcrc: finalizes a commit (CRC, pad, sync); observable on-disk and affects correctness — removal likely changes behaviour.
- lfs_cache_drop: drops caches (pcache) — side-effects on cached data and subsequent I/O; required to assess whether cache drop is necessary after a corrupt commit.
- lfs_alloc: allocates a replacement block for relocation; observable (changes free-space allocation) so must be known to judge whether relocation code is dead.
- lfs_tole32 / lfs_fromle32: endian conversion helpers used before writes/after reads; understanding whether they mutate or return values matters to assess whether conversion lines are redundant.
- LFS_MKTAG, LFS_TYPE_NAME, LFS_TYPE_TAIL, LFS_TYPE_MOVESTATE: tag construction and tag-type constants control what records are written; necessary to see whether corresponding writes are meaningful.
- LFS_ERR_CORRUPT, LFS_ERR_NOSPC, LFS_OK_RELOCATED: error/return constants used in control flow and final return value — necessary to judge observable returns and error-handling paths.
- LFS_MIGRATE: conditional compilation option that disables relocation during migration; required to understand whether relocation code can be compiled out/disabled.
- LFS_ASSERT, LFS_DEBUG, LFS_WARN: diagnostics/macros whose presence may have side-effects (assert can abort) or affect observability of operations.
- struct lfs_t (and its fields cfg, gdisk, gstate, gdelta, lfs1): the function reads/writes these fields; need their definitions to know whether changes are observable outside the function.
- struct lfs_config (metadata_max, block_size, prog_size): used to compute commit boundaries and alignment — affects what data is written.
- struct lfs_mdir_t (pair, rev, tail, split, count, off, etag): the directory object is modified; to decide if assignments are dead you must know how and when these fields are subsequently used/persisted.
- struct lfs_mattr: attribute structure passed into traverse; needed to know traverse behaviour and whether attributes written are necessary.
- struct lfs_commit (fields used): commit state held across the function; its layout and the semantics of its fields matter to commit behaviour and side-effects.
- type lfs_gstate_t: structure of gstate and its tag mask/fields (delta.tag masking) is used to decide when movestate is written.
- type lfs_pair_t / lfs_block_t: representation of block-pair values (used by pair helpers and comparisons) — needed to reason about pair comparisons and assignment effects.

In short, the above functions/macros/types determine external side-effects (block device writes, allocation, cache state, global state changes) and control-flow decisions. Without their semantics you cannot soundly decide whether code statements in lfs_dir_compact are removable (dead) without changing observable behaviour.
